@pIuraIthey still -- combined with the thagomizer, having wings informed by pterosaur anatomy rather than bat anatomy almost certainly characterizes drake as a Dinosaur Kid

@pIuraIthey the pinkie can't pronate like a wrist, so it would likely rest parallel to the other fingers at rest, causing the wing to rest directly behind drake. this might be bothersome, as pterosaurs resting their wings behind them instead of to their sides is a common misrepresentation

@pIuraIthey however, using the pinkie over morphing the wrist and palm still seems most feasible. this also allows drake to keep a relatively "normal" and function hand position with xyr 2 remaining fingers and thumb. the ring finger is detached and functions as a pteroid in the wing.

@pIuraIthey obviously, the idea of supporting one's weight on just a pinkie is dubious. i'm thinking of adding a "spike" on the end for support, similar to a bat's "thumb"; this would not be a thumb, but a detached bone spur rooted in a deactivated cancerous tumor as the "pad" of the thumb.

@pIuraIthey lengthening the metacarpals to such a drastic degree would likely be incredibly complicated, with a high chance of failure. instead, drake's wing posture mimics a pterosaur's with only the pinkie supporting xyr weight.
@pIuraIthey there are a few quirks about drake's anatomy as a dragon, because xyr anatomy is extant prior to the wings.

okay actually i went through the process of adopting a cat Recently and shelters need to stop being so restrictive too like--
and yes, it is millions. 3 million animals are euthanized by shelters every year in this country and it's still not nearly enough. there are 70 MILLION feral and abandoned cats in the USA.

but anyway, i just think being condescending at people who have a completely understandable negative reaction to the suggestion that we Must (humanely) kill MILLIONS of cats instead of like, dipshits who breed cats and release them if they don't sell is not great priorities

and don't even get me started on fucking breeding cats. there's not even a PURPOSE to specialty breeding cats because they don't perform necessary work like, say, service dogs. the exceptions here are VERY small.

this isn't even mentioning how rampant abuse with breeding is, especially for show-quality dogs. the amount of people breeding dogs for a functional work purpose vs the amount of people breeding dogs for income or aesthetic is astronomically different

and yes, i'm including specialty breeders in this. every person who wants a pretty sighthound or a cute Ethical Pug or a ragdoll specifically is someone who would have adopted an extant animal if they weren't given the option to be worse.

also, really cracking down on pet breeding is huge i feel like. one of the reasons there's such a dearth of homes available to adopt animals is because there is another more on-demand and mainstream way to acquire pets.

similar to littering, areas where there's already a population of unhoused cats actually makes people believe it's more acceptable to also abandon their cats -- especially if someone is feeding the cats.
there's a combination of factors going into those decisions, including poverty, ignorance about the effects of releasing foreign animals into the ecosystem, apathy about said effects, and, yeah, TNR.

we need a strong push for a sense of accountability in your community, including the stray animals in it. other studies have shown that one reason TNR doesn't work is that even if the entire stray population is trapped or fixed, people simply replace it by abandoning more cats.

the overlap between people who put in the time to learn the skills necessary to humanely euthanize and people who don't find killing hundreds of healthy cats traumatizing is practically nonexistent. that's how it is, and it's been tough to accept that element, but it's necessary

and i don't think we should really be putting them on an altar for sacrifice just bc YOU don't think they should have inconvenient feelings. they are PEOPLE. there is NO easy solution to the stray problem

when i was a teen and young adult my impression of credit cards was that they're a scam to put you in debt forever, but it turns out only a few things actually build your credit score, and credit cards is one of them. if you can get one with money back rewards that's even better

imagining all the times i had to beg or panic because an expense came up and i had no savings, no leeway to build savings -- could have easily been mitigated with a credit card, taking commissions more casually later, smaller than the total and paid down slowly if necessary

i had to buy groceries even though i had no money (shout out to the person who bought me a fursona bc it would have been $3 instead of $8) and i can say, best adult advice i can offer you is get a SMALL starter credit card. it will feed you during hard times AND build your credit

anyway, i was actually eating because i realized i was hungry in bed, lol. schlaf, iss, viel spaß-- gut leben

a lot of ppl -- esp ppl with eating disorders -- find the actual necessary amount of calories to successfully refeed "excessive" but this is the reality when you've avoided tens if not hundreds of thousands of calories your body needed. it remembers EVERY. ONE. with interest.

i think i didn't start sleeping reliably until a few months into refeeding, at that point a few months of around 4k-6k calories per day. needed to drink these real calorie dense shakes meant for weight regain every 20 min until i fell asleep and that worked til i was more stable
to this day i just can't sleep if i'm hungry, at all. a lot of days i find it frustrating, but i have the kind of personality where i know i need to be forced to do it or i wouldn't keep up w/it

ironically the only thing that got me to recover from my anorexia was eventually i couldn't sleep at all, could squeeze out maybe 2 hours in a week, felt like i was wet paper bring ripped up from the brain down. told myself i could never afford to skip out on sleep again either

oh and there's no known substance that compensates for sleep deprivation, even cognition enhancing and wakefulness promoting drugs... things like adderall and caffeine make subjects FEEL normal w/o actually changing reaction time, problem-solving skills, metabolic reactions, etc.
5 hours of sleep (over 60% of your daily adult need!) leaves you with the reaction time and coordination of a drunk driver. losing just TWO HOURS is already That Bad. it's wild

you're also just not your best self when sleep deprived... cognitively impaired, angrier with less willpower, physically weaker and more likely to get sick. it's not pleasant to have this version of yourself be considered your default personality

not to sound old but sleep whenever you can. sleep is not Free Time You Can Steal. your body performs A LOT of major functions exclusively during sleep. people die faster from a lack of sleep than total starvation. every hour of sleep you skimp on is cumulative damage

@literallyTYVI i'm referring to weight, and it's a political statement to say who deserves to be seen, who is desirable, who has access to representation, who is understood w/o needing to explain themselves, etc. art is inherently political imo.
relatedly, though, it eases the anxiety to try to interpret why it doesn't make sense in some kind of utilitarian way.

also, because i would pick apart the continuity of my own inner world, and obviously, at some point, it stops making sense. we are walking contradictions in a delicate balance with ourselves, our inner worlds will contradict. it causes me great anxiety that it doesn't make sense.

it doesn't make sense why nero can only grow crystals around and on alters and not the inner world itself in a literal way, but it makes sense why a gatekeeper would "shut down" alters, but wouldn't, or couldn't, otherwise physically stop them from having a go at each other.

anyway, the reason i was spurred to think about this more is actually because i was wondering if nero COULD get in between two alters fighting rather than freezing both of them. i concluded that he couldn't, because freezing them is representing a specific dissociative process.

perhaps the inner world will have some kind of furnishings, to reenact domestic experiences. it makes sense why it's there. but where did it come from, how did it get there, why does it look like that, what happens to it when the alters aren't there, etc? this doesn't matter.
usually this results in dynamics that make immediate sense to an alter, but may not have perfect "fridge logic," creating an inner world that runs on "folk physics" rather than scientific physics.

however, the mind craves order and sense, even if dissociative, so there has to be some level of narrative cohesion formed instantly from these representations, like how a dream forms from fleeting memories.

i've found that inner worlds don't have to make sense, the objects that exist in them simply represent different aggregate functions of the brain. trying to write them to always make sense will harm the intrinsic function of the inner world to a character.

reason is, after all, not just being able to puzzle through logic, but to act in a tempered, appropriate way. a person completely consumed in their own emotion is someone who can't be reasoned with... in their current state.
how much of an adult capacity to reason IS fundamentally earned through experience? that is an interesting question to have to answer to when writing the character

you would think - an adult would be able to reason that crying would stop on its own, right? they have seen others cry and know that they aren't trapped in it forever. yet the lack of firsthand experience makes the ability to logic functionally useless.

some children are afraid of crying because they have never experienced it before (in their memory) and they are afraid it will never stop. some adults who were not allowed to cry as children grow up to have a similarly motivated fear of crying because they have not experienced it

saga's an interesting character for me to write because they're not a child but they act childish. they have an adult mind in terms of capacity to understand but not a lot of conscious life experience that usually accompanies this capacity to reason and tempers emotions.

even just being in pain a lot for seemingly no reason can challenge basic ideological assumptions many healthy 20-somethings and teenagers have about what life is and what makes it the way it is, causing you to question why you exist or double down on prev. beliefs

so if you're writing a character beyond their 20s i think that's a great thing to keep in mind cuz it's not even like a little meaningless quirk that somebody's knee hurts regularly, it like affects how you move, how you socialize, what you do as hobbies, etc.

and i think sometimes older people's routines can revolve heavily around this pain and lack of energy (coupled with mounting expectations and responsibilities, like staying up later and longer w/kids, having more emotional control w/more pain, etc)

not everybody in their 30s has chronic pain but probably by 40s they are at least somewhat aware of their body not being as spritely as it used to even if they're really fit, y'know? like they are aware of what a backache or a headache is, whatever they're prone to

okay one thing the springhole article didn't mention actually is that as you get older (as early as late 20s) your body just kind of gets worse and worse. a lot of older people learn to live with some kind of chronic pain/discomfort. this can make them seem snippy "for no reason"

like if you are fine doing that or if it makes you feel seen, that's fine, but it shouldn't be a rule. if it makes you feel anxious to try to perform that cuz you just don't know all the time, you just. do not have to know. it's fine

it gives me dread even if i tell myself nobody has to know about it. i feel like i'll lose myself and not be able to get it back, but that only happens when i try to draw more lines around my behaviors and thoughts. so try to break the habit early.

there are still a lot of times where i stop in the middle of living life and wonder who i am, how do i label this experience, what name do i use for it, and it's completely useless. all it does is give me this powerful sense of dread in my chest.

especially if you're working on accepting or working together w/alters. you just get used to the presence of the experiences. you learn to relate to them or rationalize them. when you crack open the brain there are no little slices labeled w/alters. you're all using the same shit

it's fine to not know what's happening to you and to not be able to neatly segment every part of your identity so it can be consumed as a signature at the end of a tweet, as an icon that explains everything, as a discord nickname. that's honestly normal

listen for a second, ok. this took me a long time to realize. it's okay to not know "who you are" every second of every day. it's fine to blur or co-front in a weird way you can't explain or feel passive influence or not be able to tell between similar alters while you live
